TY  - JOUR
T1  - False Discovery in A/B Testing
AU  - Berman, Ron
AU  - Van den Bulte, Christophe
Y1  - 2021/12/30
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4207
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4207
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6762
EP  - 6782
VL  - 68
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We investigate what fraction of all significant results in website A/B testing is actually null effects (i.e., the false discovery rate (FDR)). Our data consist of 4,964 effects from 2,766 experiments conducted on a commercial A/B testing platform. Using three different methods, we find that the FDR ranges between 28% and 37% for tests conducted at 10% significance and between 18% and 25% for tests at 5% significance (two sided). These high FDRs stem mostly from the high fraction of true null effects, about 70%, rather than from low power. Using our estimates, we also assess the potential of various A/B test designs to reduce the FDR. The two main implications are that decision makers should expect one in five interventions achieving significance at 5% confidence to be ineffective when deployed in the field and that analysts should consider using two-stage designs with multiple variations rather than basic A/B tests.This paper was accepted by Eric Anderson, marketing.
AB  - We investigate what fraction of all significant results in website A/B testing is actually null effects (i.e., the false discovery rate (FDR)). Our data consist of 4,964 effects from 2,766 experiments conducted on a commercial A/B testing platform. Using three different methods, we find that the FDR ranges between 28% and 37% for tests conducted at 10% significance and between 18% and 25% for tests at 5% significance (two sided). These high FDRs stem mostly from the high fraction of true null effects, about 70%, rather than from low power. Using our estimates, we also assess the potential of various A/B test designs to reduce the FDR. The two main implications are that decision makers should expect one in five interventions achieving significance at 5% confidence to be ineffective when deployed in the field and that analysts should consider using two-stage designs with multiple variations rather than basic A/B tests.This paper was accepted by Eric Anderson, marketing.
